title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Interdynamic KG-9 (Legal Pre KG-9 Ban)
postcontent:
Classified a machine gun by ATF (legal to own pre-ban)

The Interdynamic KG9 pistol was made in Miami Florida for a short time in the 1981-82 timeframe by Interdynamic of America, Inc. ATF decided in January 1982 that the gun was too easy to convert into a machine gun, and therefore decided that an unmodified open bolt semi-auto KG-9 was a machine gun. ATF exempted unmodified semi-auto KG-9 pistols made before this ruling from the scope of the ruling, so there are so-called grandfathered KG-9 pistols available in the USA. The KG-9 was based on a Swedish designed machine pistol, the MP-9. After the ATF ruling the gun was redesigned into a closed bolt, striker fired pistol, the Interdynamic KG-99, which was sold in the 1982-83 timeframe. After that Interdynamic went out of buisness.

The original gun the cheap tec-9 was made to copy. Rare! Less than 1000 made! Look it up. Look up prices too. This is the short (meaning shorter barrel & no heat guard.)

http://www.gunbroker.com/Auction/ViewItem.aspx?Item=336809822 

I will trade for handguns too. There is a hairline crack in the bottom. It still works/shoots fine. Here is a video go the gun for sale http://youtu.be/3iUc8hX2938

title: For Sale:  -SOLD- 1935 Tula Hex Mosin Nagant ex-sniper, stunning condition
location: South of Farmville, Greenville, North Carolina
postcontent:
I bought this for a project gun, but it's just too nice to modify.
Someone who is a collector or who appreciates military arms in their original condition needs to have this one.
Between my father and I, we've owned dozens of Mosins over the years, and we both agree that this is the cleanest we've seen.
It's a 1935 Tula hex receiver ex-PE sniper, not the more common PU sniper of the later years.
As with all the ex-snipers, the scope and mount were removed, and the holes in the receiver were welded shut and ground off. With the PE snipers, which were typically top-mount scopes, the holes are not visible from inside. You can only tell they were there by the grind marks and slight dumpling on the outside of the receiver.
The bolt is super smooth, the best I've ever felt on a Mosin.
The stock is in great shape as well.
It includes only the cleaning rod and bayonet.
All numbers are stamped, and match, with the exception of the bayonet.
The gun is exactly as I took it out of the box. I saw what great condition it was in, and immediately decided that I'd have to buy a different one for my planned project, this one needs to go to a better home.
More photos available upon request, for serious buys only.
I'm not interested in trades, but the price is slightly negotiable.
I just want to recoup my money, since I already ordered another one for my project.

title: For Sale:  Mas 36 7.5 french rifle
postcontent:
I have an all matching L series Mas-36 for sale or trade. Serial is 67925. Stock, reciever, magazine plate, trigger guard, forend, and bolt all match.  The bolt was factory force matched and remains un-rearsenaled by CAI.  To the best of my knowledge, it was made in 1945. However, this rifle seems unique in that it is built with some pre-war parts, such as the barrel and front sight post (non-hood sight). The barrel is immaculate and looks like new with strong rifling. The beechwood stock shows some occasional wear and markings, but nothing to be concerned about and the forend is also VERY SOLID AND TIGHT, no movement whatsoever, which is a concern with these rifles and barrel harmonics. No rust or pitting anywhere.  I wanted to preserve the history of the rifle and did not refinish it. The action is very smooth, and I was surprised by the bolt. It doesn't look ergonomic, but it is one of the fastest bolts I have ever cycled, especially while still shouldered.

It shoots 7.5x54 french, which can easily be found online or reloaded. Surplus ammo can be found online for as low as $5 for 20 rds on stripper clips (avoid syrian ammo though, it's shitty). You can also reload using the same load data as .308 and same powder, primers, and bullets. Casings can EASILY be had as you can resize 6.5 swede casings, 30.06 casings, or buying PPU 7.5 brass. This is one of the cheaper milsurp rifles to feed, aside from a 7.62x54r.

I have shot around 50 rds through this rifle with absolutely no malfunctions (except for 5 rds syrian ammo with bad primers) It is very accurate at 100 yards, making nice round groupings with about 1-1.5 moa with french surplus ammo. Could probably get sub moa with handloads. 

The rifle includes its original spike bayonet and a reproduction (non-leather) sling.

These rifles are somewhat rare, and definitely underrated as they never got the chance to be proven in battle with the french army. More pics available, Asking $400 OBO 

Due to the last prospective buyer attempting to scam me, I will accept cash (if local) or USPS money order (if shipping) only.  Willing to entertain trades, but not likely, firearms only.

title: For Sale:  FNH (Herstal) PBR Patrol Bolt Rifle .308 tactical rifle -VERY RARE-
location: South of Farmville, Greenville, North Carolina
postcontent:
The wife says I have too many guns, so some must go.
This is the one I shoot the least, so...

This is an FN Herstal PBR in 308 caliber, with the 22" medium bull barrel.
In case you're not familiar, this rifle is based on the Pre-64 Winchester model 70 action, which is generally held by real shooters to be one of the finest rifle bolt actions ever made. It's rock-solid and designed to outlast me, you, and your kids. :)

The stock is a Hogue fully overmolded with a solid aluminum bedding block/pillar system, free floating the barrel.

The scope is a cheap NCStar, but it's VERY high powered (10-40x!) and worked fine the day I tried it out.

It includes a Harris-type bipod (not sure of brand, may be a Harris, not sure) and a really nice padded tactical (shock) sling.

The metal has been Duracoated in Flat Dark Earth (FDE) inside and out to protect from the elements, should you decide to hunt in foul weather.

This is an extremely rare rifle. There is exactly 1 one for sale on gunbroker, and none that I can find here on Armslist, if that tells you anything.

I've only had it to the range once (got it in trade a while back), but it shot just over 1 MOA with cheap steel case FMJ ammo at 200 yards in a nasty gusting crosswind. All the reviews and range reports I've found say that it's easily sub-MOA with decent ammo. I have no reason to doubt it.

The previous owner told me he had some bolt work done to it, so it's supposed to be slicker than stock. I don't have anything to compare it to, but the action is very smooth.

The trigger is adjustable. I'm not sure how it's set at the moment, but my "finger scale" says it feels like around 3.5 lbs with very little travel, so I'm happy.

I'm not really looking to trade, since that would defeat the purpose of "getting rid of a few guns", but you're welcome to offer if you have something you think I might like.

title: For Sale:  CZ 50 VZ 50 .32ACP
postcontent:
Comes with one 8 round magazine.

Here is some info about this hand gun.
After the Second World War the Ministry of the Interior requested a new pistol design from Česká zbrojovka Uherský Brod. The resulting pistol in .32 ACP was designed by two brothers Jan and Jaroslav Kratochvíl and closely copied from the Walther PP and PPK. The grip is made of bakelite. The pistol is fed from an 8-round single-stack magazine, located within the grip frame. Small fixed sights are located on the top of the slide. The operation is blowback - recoil causes the spring, which is located around the fixed barrel, to compress. The slide, after it reaches the end of its rearward travel, is returned forward by the recoil spring, stripping a new round from the magazine as it does so. The operation is double-action - after a round has been chambered and the hammer has been lowered, the hammer may be reengaged by squeezing the trigger.
